diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVNSink.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVNSink.cpp
index 2058df33ea33..edf86037a121 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVNSink.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVNSink.cpp
@@ -698,8 +698,10 @@ GVNSink::analyzeInstructionForSinking(LockstepReverseIterator<false> &LRI,
     if (!PHI.areAllIncomingValuesSameType())
       return std::nullopt;
     // Don't create indirect calls! The called value is the final operand.
+    // Additionally, inline asm values cannot be part of a PHI for the callee.
     if ((isa<CallInst>(I0) || isa<InvokeInst>(I0)) && OpNum == E - 1 &&
-        PHI.areAnyIncomingValuesConstant())
+        (PHI.areAnyIncomingValuesConstant() ||
+         llvm::any_of(PHI.getValues(), [](Value *V) { return isa<InlineAsm>(V); })))
       return std::nullopt;

     NeededPHIs.reserve(NeededPHIs.size());
@@ -812,6 +814,19 @@ void GVNSink::sinkLastInstruction(ArrayRef<BasicBlock *> Blocks,
       continue;
     }

+    // Safeguard: If we need a PHI for the callee operand of a call/invoke,
+    // bail out only if any incoming callee is a constant (direct call target)
+    // or inline asm. Otherwise allow sinking and creating the PHI turning
+    // different callee values into an indirect call.
+    if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(I0))
+      if (CB->isCallee(&I0->getOperandUse(O))) {
+        for (auto *I : Insts) {
+          Value *CalleeV = I->getOperand(O);
+          if (isa<InlineAsm>(CalleeV) || isa<Constant>(CalleeV))
+            return; // keep originals
+        }
+      }
+
     // Create a new PHI in the successor block and populate it.
     auto *Op = I0->getOperand(O);
     assert(!Op->getType()->isTokenTy() && "Can't PHI tokens!");

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs after running gvn-sink because the pass produces invalid IR: a phi node with inline asm values as incoming operands ("Cannot take the address of an inline asm!"). The reproducer shows a PHI of type ptr with incoming values that are inline asm call callee operands:  %.sink1 = phi ptr [ asm sideeffect ..., %sw.bb1 ], [ asm sideeffect ..., %sw.bb ]. Inline asm values (the InlineAsm callee objects) are not first-class; forming a PHI over them is invalid. GVNSink incorrectly tries to sink the inline asm call instructions across predecessors and introduces a PHI for the callee operand.

2. Analyzing opt's Log: The pass runs and verification fails on the generated PHI. The log shows no other transformations; the first mutation leading to failure is in GVNSink creating the PHI. The alias/modref info is irrelevant here. The verifier detects the illegal PHI containing inline asm values. This matches a transformation in sinkLastInstruction where PHIs are built for differing operands. The analysis phase (analyzeInstructionForSinking) determines which operands need PHIs. It attempts to avoid creating PHIs for call targets via a heuristic located at lines 698-701: // Don't create indirect calls! The called value is the final operand. if ((isa<CallInst>(I0) || isa<InvokeInst>(I0)) && OpNum == E - 1 && PHI.areAnyIncomingValuesConstant()) return std::nullopt; However, a PHI on the callee (inline asm) was still created, so this check did not trigger.

3. Root Cause Analysis: The code assumes for CallInst/InvokeInst that the "called value is the final operand" (OpNum == E - 1). This is incorrect in LLVM IR: the callee is operand 0; subsequent operands are the arguments. Thus the heuristic never examines the callee; instead it examines the last argument. Consequently GVNSink allows forming a PHI for operand 0 (callee) when callees differ between predecessors, leading to constructing a PHI of inline asm (invalid) or turning a direct call into an indirect one. In the reproducer, each predecessor ends with a distinct inline asm call (different InlineAsm objects), so operand 0 differs, GVNSink builds a PHI of those InlineAsm values, and verifier aborts. The fix must prevent PHI creation on the callee operand or abort sinking if the callee differs.

4. Proposed Edit Points(s):
Edit lines 698-701 in GVNSink.cpp inside analyzeInstructionForSinking. Replace the incorrect assumption and logic with a correct treatment of call/invoke operands:
- Recognize operand 0 as the callee.
- If operand 0 differs across predecessors, do not sink this instruction (return std::nullopt) to avoid introducing a callee PHI (which could produce an indirect call or invalid IR for inline asm).
- If operand 0 is the same, skip attempting to create a PHI for it (continue) so we only consider argument operands.
This removes reliance on incorrect OpNum==E-1 logic and directly prevents generating PHIs of InlineAsm.
Suggested replacement code:
// Do not create PHIs for the callee of a call or invoke. Operand 0 is the callee.
if (isa<CallInst>(I0) || isa<InvokeInst>(I0)) {
  if (OpNum == 0) {
    // If callees differ we cannot sink the instruction.
    if (!PHI.areAllIncomingValuesSame())
      return std::nullopt;
    // Callee identical: skip creating a PHI for it.
    continue;
  }
}
Remove the old incorrect comment and condition. This ensures inline asm callees are never placed in PHIs; if they differ sinking is aborted.

5. Conclusion: The bug stems from a mistaken assumption about operand ordering for calls/invokes causing formation of an illegal PHI over inline asm callee values. Correcting the operand index logic prevents generating invalid IR and avoids indirect call creation. After this fix, gvn-sink will no longer crash or produce the invalid PHI for the reproducer; the pass will simply refuse to sink those differing inline asm calls, preserving correctness.

